    "body": "```python\r\nimport pandas as pd\r\n# store a test DataFrame\r\nhdf_file = 'test_storage'\r\ndf = pd.DataFrame({'val': [0, 1]})\r\n#    val\r\n# 0    0\r\n# 1    1\r\ndf.to_hdf(hdf_file, 'df', format='t', data_columns=['val'])\r\n\r\n\r\n# query with filter that matches the second row\r\npd.read_hdf(hdf_file, where=['val=1'])\r\n#    val\r\n# 1    1\r\n\r\n# limit to one row with filter that match the second row\r\npd.read_hdf(hdf_file, where=['val=1'], stop=1)\r\n# Empty DataFrame\r\n# Columns:\r\n#     [val]\r\n# Index:\r\n#     []\r\n```\r\n\r\nHere the row limitation filters the result of the table query before the where condition get applied, thus returning an empty table. It's not a bug for me, but this aspect could gain to be more explicitely documented, as for example, a SQL query like `SELECT * FROM df WHERE val=1 LIMIT 1`, that seems to do the same operations would return the second row of the previous dataframe\r\n"
